</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="D17DB435FF1E091E77B384E2553B13D1" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="notes">
<paragraph id="AA55888BD7C8B19A2E33BD0DF3DC06D0" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Note.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="7FC55E9C488BBB43E034A26B0F82EDDB" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
The T-shaped hairs are difficult to observe but are distinctive. 
<taxonomicName id="0461463C1FCBA21AB60BF8A6E9A7C5F0" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="malpighipila">
<emphasis id="170DA61F949858B95E330E09384233ED" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ipomoea malpighipila</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is usually easily identified by the terminal inflorescence and obscurely pubescent, trifid leaves with narrowly oblong lobes.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
